  println!(\"{}\", s4);\r\n    s3.clear();\r\n    println!(\"s4={}\", s4);\r\n}\r\n\r\nfn try_it(s: &str) -> &str {\r\n    println!(\"{}\", s);\r\n    return gs;\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\ncompile error\r\n```\r\nerror[E0502]: cannot borrow `s3` as mutable because it is also borrowed as immutable\r\n40 |     let s4 = try_it(&s3[..]);\r\n   |                      -- immutable borrow occurs here\r\n41 |     println!(\"{}\", s4);\r\n42 |     s3.clear();\r\n   |     ^^^^^^^^^^ mutable borrow occurs here\r\n43 |     println!(\"s4={}\", s4);\r\n   |                       -- immutable borrow later used here *completely wrong, s4 has nothing to do with s3*\r\n```\r\n@cramertj 's reply\r\n\r\n> No, This is not a bug. The elided lifetimes in try_it are assuming that the output &str has the same lifetime as the input &str. To fix this, you can change try_it to -> &'static str.\r\n\r\ntwo points\r\n1. compiler actually knows whether the returned slice is s3 or not\r\n2. adding &'static is ugly and cannot solve the problem, such  as if(xxx) gs else s4 ", "closed_by": {"login": "andy-yx-chen", "id": 5241337, "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjUyNDEzMzc=", "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/5241337?v=4", "gravatar_id": "", "url": "https://api.github.com/users/andy-yx-chen", "html_url": "https://github.com/andy-yx-chen", "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/andy-yx-chen/followers", "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/andy-yx-chen/following{/other_user}", "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/andy-yx-chen/gists{/gist_id}", "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/andy-yx-chen/starred{/owner}{/repo}", "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/andy-yx-chen/subscriptions", "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/andy-yx-chen/orgs", "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/andy-yx-chen/repos", "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/andy-yx-chen/events{/privacy}", "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/andy-yx-chen/rec